
//==============================================================================
// MAIN.SRC - X Shell Entry Point and Module Loader
//==============================================================================
//
// PURPOSE:
//   Main entry point for the X Shell system. Orchestrates the loading of all
//   core modules, libraries, commands, and subsystems in the correct dependency
//   order. Handles authentication, initialization, and bootstrap operations.
//
// GREY HACK CONTEXT ARCHITECTURE - CRITICAL UNDERSTANDING:
// ========================================================
// Grey Hack's launch function CHANGES EXECUTION CONTEXT to the target system.
// This is NOT a bug - it's how the game engine works. Understanding this is
// essential to understanding why this codebase has the architecture it does.
//
// THE PROBLEM:
//   When you build a proxy chain: Home -> Hop1 -> Hop2 -> Hop3 -> Target
//   Each launch switches context. At Target, these game functions execute
//   in Target's context, NOT Home's:
//     - get_router         → Returns Target's router, not Home's
//     - include_lib(path)  → Loads from Target's /lib, not Home's
//     - File(computer, p)  → Access Target's files, not Home's
//     - get_shell          → Gets shell on Target, not Home
//
// THE SOLUTIONS (implemented throughout this codebase):
//   1. G_hasPivoted flag - Tracks when we've switched contexts via launch
//   2. G_lastIP tracking - Remembers which system we launched from
//   3. Builder.pack* pattern - Remote execution via build+launch+get_custom_object
//   4. Session objects - proxy_object/pivot_object/decoy_object manage context state
//   5. Context routing - if G_hasPivoted then Builder.packRouter else get_router
//
// WHY THREE SESSION TYPES EXIST:
//   - proxy_object: Multi-hop chains, G_hops tracking, hops command, G_proxy global
//   - pivot_object: Single exploit, simpler, no chain management, G_hasPivoted flag
//   - decoy_object: Crash recovery when launch operations partially fail
//
// DO NOT \"SIMPLIFY\" THESE PATTERNS - They exist because Grey Hack's execution
// model requires them. Any \"simplification\" will break multi-hop operations.
//
// ARCHITECTURE:
//   This file follows a strict module loading sequence to ensure all dependencies
//   are satisfied before initialization. The loading order is critical:
//   1. Kernel and core structures
//   2. Type extensions (globals, list, string, number, map, multi)
//   3. Data structures and objects
//   4. Database and server interfaces
//   5. Information/error handling systems
//   6. System modules (bash, shadow, config, gui, boot, etc.)
//   7. Network and session management
//   8. Libraries and utilities
//   9. Compression subsystem
//   10. Command system and all command modules
//
// INITIALIZATION FLOW:
//   After module loading, the system:
//   1. Checks for special bootstrap parameters (pass, shell, proxy, pivot, decoy)
//   2. Validates trusted host status or requires App ID authentication
//   3. Executes Boot.init to complete system startup
//
// BOOTSTRAP MODES:
//   Standard mode:      No parameters - full shell initialization
//   Password crack:     params[0]=key, params[1]="pass" - crack password
//   Shell crack:        params[0]=key, params[1]="shell" - crack shell
//   Proxy mode:         params[0]=key, params[1]="proxy" - initialize proxy
//   Pivot mode:         params[0]=key, params[1]="pivot" - initialize pivot
//   Decoy mode:         params[0]=key, params[1]="decoy" - initialize decoy
//
// AUTHENTICATION:
//   - First parameter must match Kernel.key or script exits with "Key Mismatch"
//   - Trusted hosts (Boot.trusted) bypass App ID authentication
//   - Non-trusted hosts must enter correct Kernel.password to proceed
//   - Empty Kernel.password allows unrestricted access (development mode)
//
// SECURITY:
//   - App ID prompt uses char(0) to hide input
//   - Infinite retry loop until correct password entered
//   - Kernel.key prevents unauthorized bootstrap mode access
//   - Trusted host whitelist for automated deployments
//
// DEPENDENCIES:
//   - All imported modules (see import_code statements below)
//   - Kernel.key: System authentication key
//   - Kernel.password: App ID for non-trusted hosts
//   - Boot.trusted: List of trusted host IP addresses
//   - Boot.init: Primary initialization function
//   - Boot.crack: Password/shell cracking bootstrap
//   - Boot.initProxy/Pivot/Decoy: Special mode bootstraps
//
// USAGE:
//   Standard launch:
//     ./x
//   
//   Bootstrap modes (requires key):
//     ./x <key> pass        # Launch in password crack mode
//     ./x <key> shell       # Launch in shell crack mode
//     ./x <key> proxy       # Initialize as proxy
//     ./x <key> pivot       # Initialize as pivot
//     ./x <key> decoy       # Initialize as decoy
//     ./x <key> decoy <ip>  # Initialize as decoy with target IP
//
// MODULE LOADING ORDER:
//==============================================================================
